result.execSummary:
This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Hearing on August 5, 2022 at 08:30 am.

08:43 AM Defendant Deandre J Beason in court with attorney Benjamin T Van Severen.  Lesli S Boese appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Defense acknowledges receipt of amended complaint and waives reading of amended complaint.

The Court conducts a colloquy with the Defense.
The Defendant requests a prelim hearing.
DDA Boese states that offer is now revoked, as it was contingent on waiving the prelim.
Attorney Van Severen states he went over offer with his client and his client is still requesting his prelim.
The Court conducts a hearing:

Officer Jacob Cde Baca, of the City of Waukesha Police Department, sworn in and testifies on direct by DDA Boese.
Cross examination by attorney Van Severen.
The witness is excused and the State rests.
The Defense rests with no testimony proffered.
The Court deems testimony closed.

The State moves for bind over.
The Defense objects to bind over.
Court finds probable cause to believe that a felony was committed and binds the defendant over for trial.

Waive reading of Information.  
NOT GUILTY PLEA ENTERED.

Attorney Van Severen requests that the Defendant be able to report to WCS in Milwaukee, instead of Waukesha.
DDA Boese states she is unsure of the reporting requirements are the same between Milwaukee WCS and Waukesha WCS and objects at this time until they know for sure.
The Court will not change WCS reporting at this time, however will let the defense bring the issue up with the Trial Court.  Hearing scheduled for August 5, 2022 at 08:30 am.
